TITLE Use toSorted() IO sort() for Immutability
USE TOSORTED() IO SORT() FOR IMMUTABILITY
.sort() mutates the array in place, which can cause bugs with React state and props. Use .toSorted() to create a new sorted array without mutation. 
Incorrect (mutates original array): 
CODE typescript 236CHARS
Correct (creates new array): 
CODE typescript 255CHARS
Why this matters in React: 
Props/state mutations break React's immutability model - React expects props and state to be treated as read-only Causes stale closure bugs - Mutating arrays inside closures (callbacks, effects) can lead to unexpected behavior 
Browser support (fallback for older browsers): 
.toSorted() is available in all modern browsers (Chrome 110+, Safari 16+, Firefox 115+, Node.js 20+). For older environments, use spread operator: 
CODE typescript 91CHARS
Other immutable array methods: 
.toSorted() - immutable sort .toReversed() - immutable reverse .toSpliced() - immutable splice .with() - immutable element replacement 